data.content:
Here's what needs to change for each item when moving to .NET 10:

---

### 1. `WebHostBuilder` → `WebApplicationBuilder`

The legacy `WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder()` hosting model is **removed** in .NET 10. Migrate to the minimal hosting model:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
var host = WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)
    .ConfigureServices(services => { ... })
    .Configure(app => { ... })
    .Build();
host.Run();

// After (.NET 10)
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
// configure services on builder.Services
var app = builder.Build();
// configure middleware on app
app.Run();
```

---

### 2. `.WithOpenApi()` → Built-in OpenAPI document generation

The `WithOpenApi()` extension method is **removed**. Use the built-in OpenAPI support introduced in .NET 9 and now the primary path in .NET 10:

```csharp
// Before
app.MapGet("/items", () => { ... }).WithOpenApi();

// After — metadata is picked up automatically
builder.Services.AddOpenApi();
// ...
app.MapOpenApi();          // serves the doc at /openapi/v1.json
app.MapGet("/items", () => { ... }); // no per-endpoint call needed
```

Use `[EndpointSummary]`, `[EndpointDescription]`, and `[Tags]` attributes to add metadata that `WithOpenApi()` lambdas previously provided.

---

### 3. `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>` — **removed**

This MSBuild property is no longer recognized. Remove it from your `.csproj`:

```diff
- <IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>true</IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>
```

The API convention analyzers are now built into the SDK.

---

### 4. `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Client` (NSwag codegen)

This package is **no longer needed for OpenAPI document generation** since documents are produced at build time by the new `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Server` support. If you're using it purely for NSwag client generation, replace the workflow:

```xml
<!-- Keep using NSwag CLI or the NSwag.ApiDescription.Client package directly -->
<PackageReference Include="NSwag.ApiDescription.Client" Version="..." />
```

If you were relying on the Swashbuckle-based pipeline to produce the doc that the client generator consumed, switch the server-side generation to the built-in `AddOpenApi()` / `MapOpenApi()` approach (item 2 above) and point your client generator at the new document path.

---

### 5. `IActionContextAccessor` as singleton — **breaks at runtime**

`IActionContextAccessor` now enforces **scoped** lifetime. Registering it as a singleton throws. Change:

```csharp
// Before
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>();

// After
builder.Services.AddHttpContextAccessor();          // already scoped-safe
builder.Services.AddScoped<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>();
// — or simply use the built-in helper —
builder.Services.AddControllers().AddActionContextAccessor();
```

---

### 6. `IPNetwork` type change in `ForwardedHeadersOptions.KnownNetworks`

`Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides.IPNetwork` is **removed**. The property now uses `System.Net.IPNetwork` (introduced in .NET 8):

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));

// After (.NET 10) — uses System.Net.IPNetwork
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new System.Net.IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));
// or parse from CIDR
options.KnownNetworks.Add(System.Net.IPNetwork.Parse("10.0.0.0/8"));
```

The constructor signature is the same (`IPAddress, int`), but it's a **struct** now instead of a class, and comes from a different namespace. Update your `using` directives and remove any reference to `Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides.IPNetwork`.

---

### 7. `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` — **removed**

The `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.RuntimeCompilation` package is no longer available for .NET 10. Use **Hot Reload** (`dotnet watch`) instead:

```bash
dotnet watch run
```

Remove from your code:

```diff
- builder.Services.AddRazorPages().AddRazorRuntimeCompilation();
- // or
- builder.Services.AddControllersWithViews().AddRazorRuntimeCompilation();
```

Remove the package reference:

```diff
- <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.RuntimeCompilation" Version="..." />
```

---

### 8. 401 → login page redirect — new default for APIs

.NET 10 changes the default `CookieAuthenticationEvents` behavior: requests with `Accept: application/json` (or no `Accept` header matching `text/html`) now receive a **bare `401`** instead of a `302` redirect. If you previously worked around this manually, you can likely **remove** your custom event handler:

```diff
  builder.Services.AddAuthentication().AddCookie(options =>
  {
-     options.Events.OnRedirectToLogin = ctx =>
-     {
-         ctx.Response.StatusCode = 401;
-         return Task.CompletedTask;
-     };
  });
```

If you still need the redirect for browser-based routes, the new behavior is content-negotiation-aware and will redirect `text/html` requests automatically.

---

### Quick checklist

| # | Item | Action |
|---|------|--------|
| 1 | `WebHostBuilder` | Rewrite to `WebApplicationBuilder` |
| 2 | `.WithOpenApi()` | Remove; use `AddOpenApi()` + `MapOpenApi()` |
| 3 | `IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers` | Delete from csproj |
| 4 | `ApiDescription.Client` | Switch to NSwag direct + built-in OpenAPI |
| 5 | `IActionContextAccessor` singleton | Register as scoped |
| 6 | `IPNetwork` | Switch to `System.Net.IPNetwork` |
| 7 | Razor runtime compilation | Remove; use `dotnet watch` |
| 8 | 401 redirect | Remove workaround; new default handles it |
